-- South African Stocks: Business Connexion, SABMiller, BHP
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2012-04-20T11:11:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-20/south-african-stocks-business-connexion-sabmiller-bhp.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index (JALSH) 
advanced for a fourth day, the longest winning streak in more
than two months, gaining less than 0.1 percent to 34,123.88 by
12:49 p.m. in Johannesburg. The index has climbed 1.3 percent
this week.  The following are among the most active equities in the
market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Platinum Ltd. (AMS)  , the biggest producer
of the metal, advanced for the first time in six days, gaining
0.4 percent to 502 rand. The company, which operates the Unki
mine in Zimbabwe, said it’s not affected by a government order
for companies to resubmit applications for prospecting rights.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest resources
company, gained 0.5 percent to 247.55 rand, a third day of
gains. Copper rose in  London , buoyed by shrinking inventories of
the metal, signs of demand from carmakers and an unexpected gain
in German business confidence.  British American Tobacco Plc (BTI)  , Europe’s largest
cigarette maker, gained to a record, adding 0.5 percent to
407.99 rand. The company bought back 270,000 of its ordinary
shares yesterday, it said in a regulatory filing today.  Mr Price Group Ltd. (MPC)  , a South African clothing and
furniture retailer, rose to a record, jumping 3 percent to
104.40 rand. Credit Suisse Group AG raised its price estimate
for the share to 110 rand, from 76 rand.  Sovereign Foods Investments Ltd. (SOV)  , a poultry
producer, rose the most in more than a week, jumping 0.8 percent
to 5.39 rand. Profit after tax rose as much as 65 percent in the
12 months through February, the company said in a trading
statement today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
